Introduction ¶

     Obesity, defined as "an abnormal or excessive fat accumulation" (World Health Organization), is a major health issue of the twenty first century which can lead to medical complications such as melitus diabetes, cardiovascular diseases, some cancers and even to a prematured death. That is why, it is primordial to understand how different factors (i.e. genetic, physiological, psychological, behavioural and environmental) impact our physical condition. The aim of this exploratoy secondary data study is to understand the relationship between the rate obesity and economic and environmental factors.

     The Food Environmental Atlas 2018 published on the platform for data science Kaggle under the license CC0: Public Domain by the United States Department of Agriculture in order to investigate interaction of socio-demographic and economic factors and the availability of healthy food options. The original dataset contains 250 variables. For this project, six variables were selected: two categorical variables the name of different states (1) and counties (2) and four continuous variables: the median household income (1) in 2015, the adult obesity rate in 2013 (2), percentages of population who has a low access to store in 2015 (4), household food insecurity (5) between 2013 and 2015. Each row represent a county in United States. As you can see, the rate of adult obesity were collected in 2013 while the other continuous variables were collected in 2015. It is the main limitation to use pre-collected data because we can not monitor the data collection and some variables which seems us to be interesting to study can be missing in a secondary data study.

     First, the dataset will be imported, cleaned and explored with pairplot. Then, several clustering models (K mean clustering with and without standardization, Principal Component Analysis) will be performed and compared to choose the best efficient. Finally, relationships between different variables will be investigasted thanks to linear regression model.

A. K mean clustering ¶

a. Determination of the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow method¶

To determine the optimal number of clusters required for K-mean clustering, two methods are used: the Elbow method and the silhouette scores method.
In [35]:
sil = []  
kmax = 10
In [36]:
for k in range(2, kmax+1):
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k).fit(dba)
  labels = kmeans.labels_
  sil.append(silhouette_score(dba, labels, metric = 'euclidean'))
In [37]:
liste = [2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,10]
In [38]:
SSE = []
K = range(2,10)
for k in K:
    kmean = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmean.fit(db0[db2])
    SSE.append(kmean.inertia_)
In [40]:
plt.figure(figsize=(18,5))
plt.plot(K, SSE)
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters: k', size = 15)
plt.ylabel('SSE', size = 12)
plt.title('Figure 2a: Determination of the optimal number of clusters k using the Elbow method ', size=20)
plt.figure(figsize=(18,5))
plt.plot(liste, sil)
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters: k', size = 15)
plt.ylabel('sil', size = 15)
plt.title('Figure 2b: Determination of the optimal number of clusters k using the silhouette score', size=20)
plt.show()

     For the Elbow method, the SSE is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center. The smaller the value of sum of squared errors is and the Elbow chart decreases, the better the clusterization is.

     The silhouette scores measures how a dot is close of other dots in the same cluster and how a dot is far of dots which belong to the nearest other cluster. A higher silhouette score is, the better the clusterization is.

     With the Elbow method (See Figure 2a above), according the criteria of determination quote previousely, the ideal number of cluster can be 3, 4, 5 or 6. The silhouette score method can select the optimal number of clusters. Indeed, for k = 3, k = 4, k = 5 and k = 6, the higher value of silhouette score is for k = 3 (See Figure 2b above). Thus, the optimal number of clusters was determined: k = 3.

     As we can visually see on these three different graphs, the method of K-mean with standardization clustering (Figure 3.(b)) does not allow a clear repartition between the clusters, all dots are merged and there are not really borders contrary to the other graphs.     The model explains only 25 % of fitted data. The intercept means that if the median household income, percentages of low access to stores and food insecurity in 2015 are null and without the influence of the location (states and counties), the rate of adult obesity will be of 33.39 %. However, it is not plausible that the median household income, percentages of low access to stores and food insecurity are equal to 0. Thus, this coefficient of regression is meaningless for this model and its only use is to place the regression line in the right place.

     If the p-value is inferior to 0.05, the coefficients are significant. For the median household income, the coefficient of - 0.0002 means that the median household income increases of 10 000, the rate of obesity decreases of 2 % when the all other variables are constant. For the percentage of food insecurity, the coefficient of 0.3666 means that if the percentage of food insecurity increases of 0.36 %, the rate of adult obesity increases of 1 % when the all other variables are constant. For the percentage of low access to stores, its coefficient (-0,0129) means that if the percentage of low access to stores increases of 0,00129 %, the rate of obesity decreases of 1 % when the all other variables are constant.

     The Multiple Linear Regression without categorical variables but with logarithmic transformation explains also 25 % of fitted data.      The model of multiple linear regression with categorical variables explains 84% of fitted data: it is almost four times more than the model of multiple linear regression without categorical variables. This means that the median household income, the percentage of food insecurity and the percentage of low access to stores in 2015 are not the only factors which impact the obesity rate in adults in the United States. The geographical location has also an impact on the rate of obesity. The intercept means that if the median household income, percentages of low access to stores and food insecurity in 2015 are null and with the influence of the location (states and counties), the rate of adult obesity will be of 18.66 %. However, it is not plausible that the median household income, percentages of low access to stores and food insecurity are equal to 0. Thus, this coefficient of regression is meaningless for this model and its only use is to place the regression line in the right place. If the p-value is inferior to 0.05, the coefficients are significant. It is the case for the median household income and the percentage of food insecurity but not for the percentage of low access to stores. For the median household income, the coefficient of - 0.000130 means that the median household income increases of 10 000, the rate of obesity decreases of 1.3 %. For the percentage of food insecurity, the coefficient 1.283155 means that the rate of adult obesity increases of 1 %, while the percentage of food insecurity increases of 1.28 % when the all other variables are constant.

          Concerning the coefficient for dummy variables, we have two references: one for the categorical variable "states": Wyoming and one for the categorical variable "counties": Ziebach. If the coefficient for dummy variables is positive, it means that on average the dependent variable is higher for this level of our categorical variable than for the reference. If the coefficient for dummy variables is negative, it means that on average the dependent variable is lower for this level of our categorical variable than for the reference. For example, Concerning the independent categorical variable "state", on average the rate of obesity in 2013 was significantly higher in Alaska, the District of Columbia, Hawaii, Idaho, Indiana, Iowa, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, Nebraska, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Oregon, Rhode Island , SC South Carolina, Utah and West Virginia than in Wyoming. On average the rate of obesity in 2013 was significantly lower in Arizona, California, Florida, Kansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Minnesota, New Mexico, North Carolina, Oklahoma, Tennessee, and Wisconsin than in Wyoming. Concerning the independant categorical variable "counties", for example on average the rate of obesity in 2013 was significantly 6.14 higher in Todd than in Ziebach and was significantly 9.02 lower in Rockland than in Ziebach.

     To be the ideal model, the line of regression schould correspond to the diagonal and dots schould be nearest the line of regression. Visually, it seems that the best model which is the closest of the perfection is the multiple linear regression with categorical variables, without logarithmic transformation and without cross - validation (Figure 5: chart colored in green). The multiple linear regression with categorical variables, with logarithmic transformation and without cross - validation : LM1_raw (Figure 5: chart colored in orange) stays a good model but visually we can estimate that the coeffient of determination will be lower than this of LM1_raw model. While there are no really differences between the same model witout and with logaritmic transformation (purple: LM_Raw/ LM_log, green/orange: LM1_raw/LM1_Log, red: MLR_Raw/MLR_Log, blue: MLR1_Raw/MLR1_Log), adding some features: our two categorical variables "states" and "county" improve considerably our model. Indeed, the risk of prediction errors decreases strongly. The cross-validation reduced the quality of our models. It is normal because the training is performed on only 20 % of the dataset, maybe the remaining of the dataset (80%) contains important informations which, unfortunately, were given up during the training process. I assume that the size of the initial dataset can impact the quantity of the loss of information. To improve this, we can for example, use 50% of dataset for the training (and therefore 50% of dataset for the testing).

    Describe a chart is interesting to have a global idea of the quality of the models but it is better to use some parameters to confirm our findings. That is why, we will compare the coefficent of determination, the Mean Squared Error, the Mean Absolute Error both the multiple linear regression models with and without cross-validation and the Root of Mean Squared Error only for multiple linear regression models cross-validation .

     The coefficient of determination: R^2 is defined as the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variables. The higher the coefficient of determination is, the better the model is. Mean Squared Error is defined as the average of the square of the difference between actual and estimated values. The Root of Mean squared Error is the standard deviation of the residuals: it is a measure to show how far the dots are from the line of regression. Mean Absolute Error is defined as the average of all absolute errors between the observed value and the true value. The lower the Mean Squared Error, the Root Mean Squared Error and the Mean Absolute Error are, the better the model is.

     These different parameters confirm the observation previously performed on the charts of the Figure 5. We can say directly that the models without categorical variables are not efficient their coefficient of determination is lower (almost 0.25 both with and without cross-validation) and their risk of errors for predicted values are higher (without cross-validation almost 3 for MAE, almost 15 for MSE, 4 for RMSE / with cross-validation: without logaritmic transformation: almost 4 for MAE, almost 3 for MSE, almost 5 for RMSE and with logaritmic transformation: almost 28 for MAE, almost 7 for MSE, almost 3 for RMSE) than those with categorical variables (with cross-validation coefficient of determination: almost 0.83). To conclude, the worse model is the multiple linear regression with cross-validation, with logarithmic transformation and with categorical variables. the best model is definitively, without possible objections after checking this quality by data vizualization and calculating different parameters of performance, the multiple linear regression model with categorical variables and without logarithmic transformation .

Conclusion ¶

    In the United States, the rate of obesity in adults in 2013, was positively associated with the percentage of low access to stores in 2015, the percentage of household food insecurity between 2013 and 2015 and was negatively associated with the median household income in 2015. Moreover, the geolocalisation in United States had an impact on the obesity rate.

     This study highlights the main drawback of secondary study: the collection of data can't be controlled. Indeed, some interesting factors to answer to our research question were missing and this show us the necessity to make some compromises or the use of data linkage with another pulicly available dataset. Thus, I had to assume that the rate of obesity is slightly modified (= increased) between 2013 and 2015. Multiple Linear Regression models will be better if we add some independent variables and point out the fact that obesity is due to several causes. Without speaking about physiological and psychological determinants, we can improve our model with other independent variables such as the level of education, the socio-professional category, the median age of the population.

  • MLR_Log: Multiple linear Regression without categorical variables with logarithmic transformation
  • MLR1_Raw: Multiple linear Regression with categorical variables without logarithmic transformation
  • MLR1_log:Multiple linear Regression with categorical variables without logarithmic transformation

Evaluate the performance of Multiple Linear Regression modeles:

  • RMSE: Root Mean Squared Error
